<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="56883" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="56883">Distribution</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="56883">
This species (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F5979094" captionText="Figure 6. Selected habitus illustrations of Gerromorpha of Mindoro A. Hebrus sp.; B. Mesovelia vittigera; C. Hydrometra mindoroensis; D. Microvelia douglasi; E. Pseudovelia cf. curvata; F. Strongylovelia mindoroensis; G. Rhagovelia mindoroensis; H. Rhagovelia raddai. Scale bars 1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.8.e56883.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/467166" pageId="0" pageNumber="56883">6</figureCitation>
D), which was originally described from Japan (
<bibRefCitation author="Scott, J." journalOrPublisher="Annals and Magazine of Natural History, Series 4." pageId="0" pageNumber="56883" pagination="423 - 452" refId="B5981019" refString="Scott, J., 1874. On a collection of Hemiptera Heteroptera from Japan. Descriptions of various new genera and species. Annals and Magazine of Natural History, Series 4. 14 (83): 423 - 452" title="On a collection of Hemiptera Heteroptera from Japan. Descriptions of various new genera and species" volume="14" year="1874">Scott 1874</bibRefCitation>
), is widely distributed in the Oriental, Australian and Melanesian Regions reaching eastwards to the remote islands of the West Pacific Region (
<bibRefCitation author="Andersen, N. M." journalOrPublisher="Invertebrate Taxonomy" pageId="0" pageNumber="56883" pagination="261 - 348" refId="B5981517" refString="Andersen, N. M., Weir, T. A., 2003. The genus Microvelia Westwood in Australia (Hemiptera: Heteroptera: Veliidae). Invertebrate Taxonomy 17 (2): 261 - 348" title="The genus Microvelia Westwood in Australia (Hemiptera: Heteroptera: Veliidae)" volume="17" year="2003">Andersen and Weir 2003</bibRefCitation>
). See Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F5979098" captionText="Figure 7. Distribution of the collecting sites of Gerromorpha material (part 1) treated in this study." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.8.e56883.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/467247" pageId="0" pageNumber="56883">7</figureCitation>
for the additional records.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="56883" type="taxon discussion">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="56883">Taxon discussion</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="56883">
See 
<bibRefCitation author="Andersen, N. M." journalOrPublisher="The Raffles Bulletin of Zoology" pageId="0" pageNumber="56883" pagination="111 - 116" refId="B5978683" refString="Andersen, N. M., Yang, C. M., Zettel, H., 2002. Notes on the Microveliinae of Singapore and Peninsular Malaysia with the description of the two new species of Microvelia WESTWOOD (Hemiptera - Heteroptera: Veliidae. The Raffles Bulletin of Zoology 50 (1): 111 - 116" title="Notes on the Microveliinae of Singapore and Peninsular Malaysia with the description of the two new species of Microvelia WESTWOOD (Hemiptera - Heteroptera: Veliidae" volume="50" year="2002">Andersen et al. (2002)</bibRefCitation>
for identification. The species is rarely collected in the Island.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="56883" type="habitat">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="56883">Habitat</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="56883">
The species was found on stream banks, specifically in side pools (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F5978769" captionText="Figure 3. Microhabitats sampled with their respective label codes, as listed above. A. side pool with mineral deposits (&quot; t &quot;); B. littoral pool with mineral deposits (&quot; b &quot;); C. bottom gravel in running water (&quot; c &quot;); D. leaf packs trapped in riffles (&quot; d &quot;); E. leaf litter in rivulet (&quot; k &quot;); F. rock surface in riffle (&quot; g &quot;); G. root packs in running water (&quot; h &quot;); H. neustic in running water (&quot; z &quot;)." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.8.e56883.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/434247" pageId="0" pageNumber="56883">3</figureCitation>
B), such as at site BR3 (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F5978778" captionText="Figure 2. Sampling sites at the Baroc River basin (Roxas, southern Mindoro). A. lower Baroc River (BR 3); B. Hinundungan River from Hinagdanan Falls (HR 2); C. upper Taugad Daka River (TDR 4); D. small tributary of the Taugad River (TUC)." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.8.e56883.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/434062" pageId="0" pageNumber="56883">2</figureCitation>
A).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
